_exec_summary.SummaryText:
From: Final Regulations
Governor's Office of Emergency Services

The owner or operator shall provide in the RMP an executive summary that includes a brief description of the following elements:

(a) The accidental release prevention and emergency response policies at the stationary source;
(b) The stationary source and regulated substances handled;
(c) The worst-case release scenario(s) and the alternate release scenarios(s), including administrative controls and mitigation measure to limit the distances for each reported scenario;
(d) The general accidental release prevention program and chemical-specific prevention steps;
(e) The five-year accident history;
(f) The emergency response program, and;
(g) Planned changes to improve safety.


DRAFT - RMP EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

Introduction
The McKinleyville Community Services District utilizes chlorine to provide disinfection of treated wastewater at their Waste Water Management Facility located off of Hiller Road in McKinleyville.  In addition, the District has the ability, although it has never been utilized, to provide additional chlorination of the District's potable water supply.  The District's potable water chlorination equipment is located at the North Bank Road Pump Station, where the District's turnout is received from the wholesaler, the Humboldt Bay Municipal Water District.

In conjunction with these facilities and functions, the District stores liquid chlorine and maintains piping and plumbing to facilitate the injection of chlorine to affect disinfection of pathogenic organisms.  Liquid chlorine is stored in one-ton containers at the Waste Water Management Facility, and in 150-lb. cylinders at the North Bank Road Pump Station.  In order to facilitate ordering and delivery of the one-ton cylinders, the District occasionally stores liquid chlorine in excess of 2,500 lbs.

